</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Razamatazz Pizzazz, Archmage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Summary</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;The Holy Trinity&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> refers to the most popular group style, centered around a player tank, with a healer and a slower to support them.  Too many players believe that there are no good alternatives, and worse: that mages do not fare well in those groups.  However, this is not true.  The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Pet-Centered Group</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a powerful alternative that avoids many flaws of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Holy Trinity,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and in such groups, mages are King.  All mages owe it to themselves and their fellow casters to master this group style.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Holy Trinity</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The most obvious and popular group style is centered around a player tank, often called the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Main Tank</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, most usually a warrior.  The strategy is simple and compelling.  The main tank holds the attention of a single foe while the damage dealers kill the enemy.  A good healer is required to keep the main tank alive, as they are ideally taking all the damage the enemy deals.  A slower reduces the damage output of the enemy enormously, and is often considered necessary.  Combat with additional enemies is defered through a variety of techniques until the main enemy is defeated.<br>
<br>
This strategy has many advantages.  It is simple, well known, and broadly applicable.  There is a steady population of tanks, healers, and slowers, so these groups can be relatively easy to form.  Most players know their roles in such groups, and perform adequately well.  They can enjoy high throughput of foes, and hence, experience.  Most players prefer this style of play to the exclusion of all others.  Some even go far as to claim that all other group styles are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;gimp&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and a waste of time.  Indeed, many players are unaware that there are alternatives.<br>
<br>
However, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Holy Trinity&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> has numerous disadvantages, which are largely ignored by its legion of advocates.  It can be difficult for players outside the main trinity classes to recruit such a group.  Unless the trinity is complete, the group will not function, so a shortage of appropriate trinity class characters can make it time consuming or even impossible to get started.  There is much competition for the role of damage dealer in trinity groups, and usually a surplus of damage dealers.  This can be frustrating for the magician, as many players still do not appreciate mage damage output.<br>
<br>
Because trinity groups depend so much on the trinity itself, the group is very <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;brittle.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  If any key member of the trinity leaves and is not replaced, then the group must break up and usually abandon their camp to others.<br>
<br>
These flaws arise because the trinity is so dependent on the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Main Tank</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Should the main tank die, the group is not likely to fair well.  All effort must be made to sustain the main tank, hence the healer and the slower.  Since the main trinity classes are not very good damage dealers, redundancy in the trinity is usually avoided.  Likewise, good damage dealers are generally not trinity classes, one does not usually make a good substitute for the other.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Pet-Centered Group</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Pet-Centered Group</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> avoids having a main player tank at all, and instead relies on one or more pets to hold the attention of the enemy.  In contrast to player tanks, there is almost no cost or consequence to the death of a pet, which can be easily replaced.  Thus neither a healer nor a slower is necessary, although either is welcome.  The composition of a pet-centered group is very flexible.  The minimum requirements are at least one pet class, and no player melees.  As long as a sufficient number of pets can be sustained, a pet-centered group can add or lose any number of priests and casters and proceed largely as before, adjusting the pull rate to the current size and composition of the group.  Thus pet-centered groups are easier to recruit and easier to sustain than trinity groups.  Pet-centered groups have high damage output, and tend to dispatch foes more quickly than trinity groups.  And as elementals are the kings of pets, so mages rule pet-centered groups.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>One Pet to Rule Them All</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The simplest pet-centered group has a single elemental tanking <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(or perhaps a warder)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, while the rest of the group supports that pet and deals damage.  It is very similar in style to the trinity group, and like it, requires at least a healer and ideally a slower.  While the elemental is generally not as good a tank as a player <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(it has lower AC and does not taunt as well)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, healing pets generates no aggro for the healer, and a dead pet is much more easily and quickly replaced than a dead player.  Aggro must be carefully managed, for pets almost never take aggro from a player that is within melee range.  This is not the best form of pet-centered group, but is acceptable for very small groups.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Dipole of Death</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
When there are two pets, these are best set to guard points some distance from each other, forming a line segment.  Ideally, the mob is pulled to the middle point between them, and engaged from two sides at once.  Thus the mob must expose their back to one pet or the other.  Usually if there is more than one pet, healing is not necessary.  As soon as one pet dies, the other takes aggro, while the dead pet is simply replaced.  This also reduces the necessity for a slower, although a slower is almost always welcome.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The more the merrier</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The more pets, the easier the pet-centered group is to sustain, and the less important the death of any single pet is.  At the same time, more pets kill the enemy faster, so fewer pets need be replaced.  The more pets, the easier it is for them to hold aggro, and the better able to cope with adds.  Indeed, a group with three or more pets may prefer to deliberately camp where adds are common, avoiding the need to pull, and so maintaining a higher sustained kill rate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Fifth Element</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
As elementals are the king of pets, so mages are the king of pet-centered groups.  Of all the summonable pets, elementals are the toughest and deal the most damage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(although warders can be comparable)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Mages have a variety of elementals available to them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Earth</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the simplest and most basic elemental to use in pet-centered groups.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Root</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> helps it take, keep, and regain aggro, and elemental root can hold creatures that are otherwise immune to root or snare.  The fewer pets and the more aggravating damage dealers there are in the group, the more root will save the day.  However, root means that the nearest pet will hold aggro, and other pets generally attack from a closer distance than elementals.  Except for warders or charmed creatures, non-elemental pets do not tank well, and will die quickly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Fire</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an acceptable pet at lower levels with not many pets in the group, as its damage shield is quite impressive.  However, depending on the pet mix, it may not have aggro, and its damage shield then is wasted.  Post-50 fire pets act like NPC wizards, largely casting spells instead of meleeing, and are probably not a good choice.  Indeed, most mages are dubious about the post-50 fire pets in general, although they do have their advocates.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Air</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> elementals stun, and where applicable this can be valuable against casters and hard hitting mobs.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Water</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> elementals are another good choice, especially post-50 when they act as rogues and can backstab the enemy.  If the group contains a necromancer, you may decide to fear-kite, and the post-50 water elementals are ideal for this.  If the group has enough pets and earth elementals can be avoided, post-50 is an excellent choice for killing the mob more quickly when it turns to flee.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Epic</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an awesome pet, especially pre-60.  A pet-centered group with multiple epics is a sight to behold.  The epic has high damage output, stuns, and an innate damage shield.  If root is not necessary, the epic is almost always the best choice if available.  Its only downside in these groups is that it is more costly and time consuming to replace the epic.  Against high DPS mobs, it may be a good idea for the epic mage to memorize a second pet, just in case.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Beast Faster with Beast Master</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Beastlords</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are a welcome addition to any pet-centered group.  Not only are warders comparable to elementals in their toughness and damage output, but the lord brings slows, buffs and heals to the group.  However, the warder usually takes aggro from the elementals, and costs more time and mana to replace.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Slightly Stained Souls for Sale</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Necromancers</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bring a variety of abilities to a pet-centered group.  If the geography allows it, the group can <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>fear-kite</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, that is snare and fear the enemy so it flees rather than fight.  The mage should <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Malosini</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the enemy so fear and snare stick better, and water elementals are ideal.  Necromancers also can mezz and heal, which is very useful.  However, their undead pets tend to take aggro from elementals and die rather quickly if tanking.  If fear-kiting is not possible and tanking is required, the necromancer may considered doing without his pet entirely.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Some Enchanted Evening....</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Enchanters</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bring a great deal to a pet-centered group.  Besides the obvious mind candy, they can slow and mezz adds.  Charmed mobs make very powerful pets, often dwarfing summoned pets for damage and hitpoints.  However, this can be risky.  As mentioned previously, it can be difficult for pets to take aggro from players, and enchanters are aggromaniacs.  Therefore earth elementals may be best, especially if the enchanter is not used to this group style.  Enchanters also have a relative weak summoned pet, which can be useful, but tends to take aggro from elementals.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>We're off to see the Wizard!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Wizards</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are a good addition to pet groups, as long as they can avoid aggro.  They have a variety of fast, efficient, and hard nukes.  Although they have a summoned sword pet, it is useless in pet groups as it takes aggro and dies almost instantly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Funny, you don't look Druish</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Druids</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bring hukes, heals and buffs.  Unless there are a lot of pets or the groups is fear-kiting, they probably should leave <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Boo Boo Bear</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at home, since he tends to take aggro from the stronger pets.  In some zones, animals can be charmed to great effect.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>In California, we call them Shapersons</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Shaman</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are a great addition to nearly any group.  Slow is an absurdly powerful ability, heals are nice, and their combat buffs are second to none.  Their wolf pet tends to take aggro from stronger pets.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Father forgive me, for I have sinned</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Clerics</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, while not as valuable as in trinity groups, are also welcome.  They can easily sustain an elemental tank without risking aggro.  Death is always a possibility, and ressurection a welcome relief.  They have a hammer pet, but it always takes aggro from stronger pets and dies quickly.<br>
<br>
In general, healers reduce the need to replace pets, and so allow the pet owners to devote more of their effort to dealing damage as God Intended: by casting a vengeful rain of fire and steel upon their foes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(being naughty in His sight)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>/ooc Non-melees wanted for pet-centered group</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
In general, melees are not welcome in pet-centered groups.  Pets almost never take aggro when a player is within melee range of a mob, so player melees negate the whole premise of this strategy.  There are some exceptions.  With the right AA, high level <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rangers</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can sustain significant damage through archery alone, and can also contribute to the group by pulling.  Although the details are not well understood, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Monks</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> appear to have some kind of aggro reduction factor, and one or two monks can share aggro with epic and air pets so long as the elementals outnumber the monks and root is not used. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rogues</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> might be useful when fearkiting, but are otherwise unwelcome in pet-centered groups.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Bards</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can mezz and charm, but must be careful to maintain their distance from the melee.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Proof is in the Pudding</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You may be skeptical that anything other than a group based on the holy trinity can be worthwhile.  Don't take my word for it: <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">try it yourself</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  Get some mages, casters and priests together, and see how fast the mobs die.<br>
<br>
